{{short description|An informal term for unclassified or poorly understood genetic material }}
'''Biological dark matter''' is an informal term for unclassified or poorly understood genetic material. This genetic material may refer to genetic material produced by unclassified [[microorganism]]s.  By extension, biological dark matter may also refer to the un-isolated microorganism whose existence can only be inferred from the genetic material that they produce. Alternatively, the genetic material may refer to [[non-coding DNA]] (junk DNA)<ref name=Nessa>{{cite book| last1=Carey| first1=Nessa | name-list-format = vanc | authorlink =Nessa Carey|title=Junk DNA: A Journey Through the Dark Matter of the Genome| date=2015| publisher=Columbia University Press| isbn=9780231170840}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Kolata |first=Gina | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/06/science/far-from-junk-dna-dark-matter-proves-crucial-to-health.html?pagewanted=all)&_r=0 |title=Bits of Mystery DNA, Far From 'Junk', Play Crucial Role |work=The New York Times |date=5 September 2012 |access-date=2015-09-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Boyle |first=Rebecca | name-list-format = vanc |url=http://www.popsci.com/science/article/2012-09/encode-project-sheds-light-human-genomes-dark-matter |title=Inside the Mysterious Dark Matter of the Human Genome |work=Popular Science |date=6 September 2012 |access-date=2015-09-09 }}</ref> and [[non-coding RNA]] produced by known organisms.<ref>{{cite news | vauthors = Pugh BF, Voss K | url=http://science.psu.edu/news-and-events/2013-news/Pugh9-2013 |title=Scientists Discover the Origins of Genomic "Dark Matter" |work=Penn State Science |date=13 September 2013 |access-date=2015-09-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://actu.epfl.ch/news/scientists-shed-some-light-on-biological-dark-matt/ |title=Scientists shed some light on biological "dark matter" |work=Ecole Polytechnique Federale de Lausanne |date=20 January 2014 |access-date=2015-09-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = van Bakel H, Nislow C, Blencowe BJ, Hughes TR | title = Most "dark matter" transcripts are associated with known genes | journal = PLoS Biology | volume = 8 | issue = 5 | pages = e1000371 | date = May 2010 | pmid = 20502517 | pmc = 2872640 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pbio.1000371 | editor1-last = Eddy | editor1-first = Sean R. }}</ref>

== Genomic dark matter ==
{{main|Junk DNA}}
Much of the genomic dark matter is thought to originate from ancient [[transposable elements]] and from other low-complexity repetitive elements.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = de Koning AP, Gu W, Castoe TA, Batzer MA, Pollock DD | title = Repetitive elements may comprise over two-thirds of the human genome | journal = PLoS Genetics | volume = 7 | issue = 12 | pages = e1002384 | date = December 2011 | pmid = 22144907 | pmc = 3228813 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pgen.1002384 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Maumus F, Quesneville H | title = Deep investigation of Arabidopsis thaliana junk DNA reveals a continuum between repetitive elements and genomic dark matter | journal = PLOS ONE | volume = 9 | issue = 4 | pages = e94101 | year = 2014 | pmid = 24709859 | pmc = 3978025 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0094101 | bibcode = 2014PLoSO...994101M }}</ref>  Uncategorized [[genetic material]] is found in [[humans]] and in several other [[organism]]s.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wu D, Wu M, Halpern A, Rusch DB, Yooseph S, Frazier M, Venter JC, Eisen JA | title = Stalking the fourth domain in metagenomic data: searching for, discovering, and interpreting novel, deep branches in marker gene phylogenetic trees | journal = PLOS ONE | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = e18011 | date = March 2011 | pmid = 21437252 | pmc = 3060911 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0018011 | bibcode = 2011PLoSO...618011W }}</ref><ref name="new scientist">{{cite journal | url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn20265-biologys-dark-matter-hints-at-fourth-domain-of-life/ | title=Biology's 'dark matter' hints at fourth domain of life | publisher=Reed Business Information Ltd. | journal=New Scientist | volume=209 | issue=2805 | pages=16 | date=March 18, 2011 | access-date=August 23, 2015 | last = Barras | first = Colin | name-list-format = vanc | bibcode=2011NewSc.209Q..16B | doi=10.1016/S0262-4079(11)60657-X }}</ref> Their [[Phylogenetics|phylogenetic]] novelty could indicate the cellular [[organism]]s or [[virus]]es from which they evolved.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kemsley |first=Tamarra | name-list-format = vanc |title=New Study on "Dark Matter" of Biology Fills in Major Holes in Tree of Life |work=Nature World News |date=13 July 2015 |url=https://www.natureworldnews.com/articles/2972/20130715/new-study-dark-matter-biology-fills-major-holes-tree-life.htm |access-date=2015-09-09 }}</ref>

== Unclassified microorganisms ==

Up to 99% of all living [[microorganism]]s cannot be [[microbiological culture|cultured]],<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Huang WE, Song Y, Xu J | title = Single cell biotechnology to shed a light on biological 'dark matter' in nature | journal = Microbial Biotechnology | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 15–6 | date = January 2015 | pmid = 25627841 | pmc = 4321360 | doi = 10.1111/1751-7915.12249 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lok |first=Corie | name-list-format = vanc |url=http://www.nature.com/news/mining-the-microbial-dark-matter-1.17774 |title=Mining the microbial dark matter |work=Nature News |date=16 June 2015 |access-date=2015-09-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Check-Hayden |first=Erika | name-list-format = vanc |url=http://www.nature.com/news/researchers-glimpse-microbial-dark-matter-1.13361 |title=Researchers glimpse microbial 'dark matter' |work=Nature News |date=14 July 2013 |access-date=2015-09-09 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gronstal |first= Aaron L. | name-list-format = vanc |title=Studying Biology’s Dark Matter |work=NASA Astrobiology Institute |date=4 November 2011 |access-date=2015-09-09 |url=https://www.astrobio.net/also-in-news/studying-biologys-dark-matter-2/ }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://microbialdarkmatter.org/index.php/11-intro/2-what-is-microbial-dark-matter-and-why-should-we-explore-it |title=What is Microbial Dark Matter and why should we explore it? |last=Rinke |first=Chris | name-list-format = vanc |work=Microbial Dark Matter |date=2015 |access-date=2015-09-09 }}</ref> so few functional insights exist about the [[metabolism|metabolic potential]] of these organisms.

Sequences that are believed to be derived from unknown microbes are referred to as the ‘Microbial Dark Matter,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lok C | title = Mining the microbial dark matter | journal = Nature | volume = 522 | issue = 7556 | pages = 270–3 | date = June 2015 | pmid = 26085253 | doi = 10.1038/522270a | bibcode = 2015Natur.522..270L }}</ref> the ‘Dark Virome’,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hannigan GD, Meisel JS, Tyldsley AS, Zheng Q, Hodkinson BP, SanMiguel AJ, Minot S, Bushman FD, Grice EA | title = The human skin double-stranded DNA virome: topographical and temporal diversity, genetic enrichment, and dynamic associations with the host microbiome | journal = mBio | volume = 6 | issue = 5 | pages = e01578-15 | date = October 2015 | pmid = 26489866 | pmc = 4620475 | doi = 10.1128/mBio.01578-15 }}</ref> or ‘Dark Matter Fungi’ <ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ryberg M, Nilsson RH | title = New light on names and naming of dark taxa | journal = MycoKeys | volume = 30 | issue = 30 | pages = 31–39 | date = 2018 | pmid = 29681731 | pmc = 5904500 | doi = 10.3897/mycokeys.30.24376 }}</ref>  Such sequences are not rare.  It has been estimated that in material from humans, between 40 and 90% of viral sequences are from Dark Matter.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Aggarwala V, Liang G, Bushman FD | title = Viral communities of the human gut: metagenomic analysis of composition and dynamics | journal = Mobile DNA | volume = 8 | pages = 12 | date = 2017 | pmid = 29026445 | pmc = 5627405 | doi = 10.1186/s13100-017-0095-y }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kramná L, Kolářová K, Oikarinen S, Pursiheimo JP, Ilonen J, Simell O, Knip M, Veijola R, Hyöty H, Cinek O | title = Gut virome sequencing in children with early islet autoimmunity | journal = Diabetes Care | volume = 38 | issue = 5 | pages = 930–3 | date = May 2015 | pmid = 25678103 | doi = 10.2337/dc14-2490 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Krishnamurthy SR, Wang D | title = Origins and challenges of viral dark matter | journal = Virus Research | volume = 239 | pages = 136–142 | date = July 2017 | pmid = 28192164 | doi = 10.1016/j.virusres.2017.02.002 }}</ref>  Human blood contains over three thousand different DNA sequences which can not be identified.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kowarsky M, Camunas-Soler J, Kertesz M, De Vlaminck I, Koh W, Pan W, Martin L, Neff NF, Okamoto J, Wong RJ, Kharbanda S, El-Sayed Y, Blumenfeld Y, Stevenson DK, Shaw GM, Wolfe ND, Quake SR | title = Numerous uncharacterized and highly divergent microbes which colonize humans are revealed by circulating cell-free DNA | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 114 | issue = 36 | pages = 9623–9628 | date = September 2017 | pmid = 28830999 | pmc = 5594678 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.1707009114 }}</ref>  

Algorithms have been developed that examine sequences for similarities to bacterial 16S RNA sequences,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bowman JS | title = Identification of Microbial Dark Matter in Antarctic Environments | journal = Frontiers in Microbiology | volume = 9 | pages = 3165 | date = 2018 | pmid = 30619224 | pmc = 6305705 | doi = 10.3389/fmicb.2018.03165 }}</ref> K-mer similarities to known viruses,<ref name=":0">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ren J, Ahlgren NA, Lu YY, Fuhrman JA, Sun F | title = VirFinder: a novel k-mer based tool for identifying viral sequences from assembled metagenomic data | journal = Microbiome | volume = 5 | issue = 1 | pages = 69 | date = July 2017 | pmid = 28683828 | pmc = 5501583 | doi = 10.1186/s40168-017-0283-5 }}</ref>  specific features of codon usage,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Bzhalava Z, Tampuu A, Bała P, Vicente R, Dillner J | title = Machine Learning for detection of viral sequences in human metagenomic datasets | journal = BMC Bioinformatics | volume = 19 | issue = 1 | pages = 336 | date = September 2018 | pmid = 30249176 | pmc = 6154907 | doi = 10.1186/s12859-018-2340-x }}</ref> or for inferring the existence of proteins.<ref name=":1">{{cite journal | vauthors = Barrientos-Somarribas M, Messina DN, Pou C, Lysholm F, Bjerkner A, Allander T, Andersson B, Sonnhammer EL | title = Discovering viral genomes in human metagenomic data by predicting unknown protein families | journal = Scientific Reports | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | pages = 28 | date = January 2018 | pmid = 29311716 | pmc = 5758519 | doi = 10.1038/s41598-017-18341-7 | bibcode = 2018NatSR...8...28B }}</ref>   These approaches have suggested, for example, the existence of a novel [[bacteriophage]] of the [[microviridae]] family,<ref name=":1" /> and a novel bacterioidales-like phage.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Ogilvie LA, Bowler LD, Caplin J, Dedi C, Diston D, Cheek E, Taylor H, Ebdon JE, Jones BV | title = Genome signature-based dissection of human gut metagenomes to extract subliminal viral sequences | journal = Nature Communications | volume = 4 | pages = 2420 | date = 2013 | pmid = 24036533 | pmc = 3778543 | doi = 10.1038/ncomms3420 | bibcode = 2013NatCo...4E2420O }}</ref>  Other studies have suggested the existence of 264 new viral genera, discovered in publicly available databases,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Roux S, Hallam SJ, Woyke T, Sullivan MB | title = Viral dark matter and virus-host interactions resolved from publicly available microbial genomes | journal = eLife | volume = 4 | date = July 2015 | pmid = 26200428 | pmc = 4533152 | doi = 10.7554/eLife.08490 }}</ref> and a study of human blood suggested that 42% of people have at least one previously unknown virus each, adding up to 19 different new genera.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Moustafa A, Xie C, Kirkness E, Biggs W, Wong E, Turpaz Y, Bloom K, Delwart E, Nelson KE, Venter JC, Telenti A | title = The blood DNA virome in 8,000 humans | journal = PLoS Pathogens | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = e1006292 | date = March 2017 | pmid = 28328962 | pmc = 5378407 | doi = 10.1371/journal.ppat.1006292 }}</ref> A comprehensive study of DNA sequences from multiple human samples inferred the existence of 4,930 species of microbes of which 77% were previously unreported.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Pasolli E, Asnicar F, Manara S, Zolfo M, Karcher N, Armanini F, Beghini F, Manghi P, Tett A, Ghensi P, Collado MC, Rice BL, DuLong C, Morgan XC, Golden CD, Quince C, Huttenhower C, Segata N | title = Extensive Unexplored Human Microbiome Diversity Revealed by Over 150,000 Genomes from Metagenomes Spanning Age, Geography, and Lifestyle | journal = Cell | volume = 176 | issue = 3 | pages = 649–662.e20 | date = January 2019 | pmid = 30661755 | pmc = 6349461 | doi = 10.1016/j.cell.2019.01.001 }}</ref>   Health-related findings include a prophage that might be associated with cirrhosis of the liver,<ref name=":0" /> and seven novel sequences from children with type-1 diabetes that have characteristics of viruses.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cinek O, Kramna L, Lin J, Oikarinen S, Kolarova K, Ilonen J, Simell O, Veijola R, Autio R, Hyöty H | title = Imbalance of bacteriome profiles within the Finnish Diabetes Prediction and Prevention study: Parallel use of 16S profiling and virome sequencing in stool samples from children with islet autoimmunity and matched controls | journal = Pediatric Diabetes | volume = 18 | issue = 7 | pages = 588–598 | date = November 2017 | pmid = 27860030 | doi = 10.1111/pedi.12468 }}</ref>  Although they might exist, no organisms that clearly cause human disease have been discovered in the Dark Matter.

