{{membrane-protein-stub}}

{{Pfam box | Symbol = A3P053 | Name = Alanine/glycine:cation symporter (AGCS) family protein | image = | width = | caption = | Pfam = PF01235 | Pfam_clan = | InterPro = IPR001463 | SMART = | PROSITE = PS00873 | SCOP = | TcdB = 2.A.25 | OPM family = | OPM protein = | PDB = }} Members of the '''Alanine or Glycine:Cation Symporter (AGCS) Family''' ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.25 TC# 2.A.25]) transport [[alanine]] and/or [[glycine]] in [[symport]] with Na<sup>+</sup> and or H<sup>+</sup>.
==Structure and function== Known proteins in the AGCS family are between 445 and 550 amino acyl residues in length and possess 8 to 12 putative transmembrane α-helical spanners. Members may possess 11 transmembrane segments (TMSs), as seems to be true for DagA ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.25.1.1 TC# 2.A.25.1.1]) and AgcS ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.25.1.3 TC# 2.A.25.1.3]), although Acp ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.25.1.2 TC# 2.A.25.1.2]) has only 8 TMSs, perhaps the result of truncation. As of early 2016, there does not appear to be any 3D crystal structure data available for these proteins. Members of the AGCS family have been found in bacteria and archaea, such as extremophile halotolerant cyanobacterium ''Aphanothece halophytica,'' and thermophilic bacteria, ''Bacillus'' ''PS3''.<ref name="Bualuang">{{cite journal | vauthors = Bualuang A, Kageyama H, Tanaka Y, Incharoensakdi A, Takabe T | title = Functional characterization of a member of alanine or glycine: cation symporter family in halotolerant cyanobacterium Aphanothece halophytica | journal = Bioscience, Biotechnology, and Biochemistry | volume = 79 | issue = 2 | pages = 230–5 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25421789 | doi = 10.1080/09168451.2014.968091 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kanamori M, Kamata H, Yagisawa H, Hirata H | title = Overexpression of the alanine carrier protein gene from thermophilic bacterium PS3 in Escherichia coli | journal = Journal of Biochemistry | volume = 125 | issue = 3 | pages = 454–9 | date = March 1999 | pmid = 10050032 | doi = 10.1093/oxfordjournals.jbchem.a022308 }}</ref> As of 2015, only three members of the family have been functionally characterized. These proteins show limited sequence similarity in the APC family ([http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.3 TC# 2.A.3]).<ref name=TCDB/> As of early 2016, there do not appear to be any crystal structures available for members of the AGCS family.
===Transport reaction=== The generalized transport reaction catalyzed by the AGCS family is:<ref name=TCDB>{{cite web|last1=Saier|first1=MH | name-list-format = vanc |title=2.A.25 The Alanine or Glycine:Cation Symporter (AGCS) Family|url=http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.25|website=Transporter Classification Database|publisher=Saier Lab Bioinformatics Group / SDSC}}</ref>
alanine or glycine (out) + Na<sup>+</sup> or H<sup>+</sup> (out) → alanine or glycine (in) + Na<sup>+</sup> or H<sup>+</sup> (in).
==Proteins in the AGCS family== There are currently 10 proteins belonging to the AGCS family. These proteins and their descriptions can be found in the [http://www.tcdb.org/search/result.php?tc=2.A.25.2 Transporter Classification Database].
