The '''Peptidoglycolipid Addressing Protein (GAP) Family'''<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Sondén | first = Berit | last2 = Kocíncová | first2 = Dana | last3 = Deshayes | first3 = Caroline | last4 = Euphrasie | first4 = Daniel | last5 = Rhayat | first5 = Lamya | last6 = Laval | first6 = Françoise | last7 = Frehel | first7 = Claude | last8 = Daffé | first8 = Mamadou | last9 = Etienne | first9 = Gilles | date = 2005-10-01 | title = Gap, a mycobacterial specific integral membrane protein, is required for glycolipid transport to the cell surface | journal = Molecular Microbiology | volume = 58 | issue = 2 | pages = 426–440 | doi = 10.1111/j.1365-2958.2005.04847.x | issn = 0950-382X | pmid = 16194230 }}</ref> is a member of the [[Lysine Exporter|Lysine Exporter (LysE) Superfamily]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tsu|first=Brian V.|last2=Saier|first2=Milton H.|date=2015-01-01|title=The LysE Superfamily of Transport Proteins Involved in Cell Physiology and Pathogenesis|journal=PLoS One|volume=10|issue=10|pages=e0137184|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0137184|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4608589|pmid=26474485}}</ref> It is listed as item 2.A.116 in the [[Transporter Classification Database]]. The mechanism of its action is not known, but this family has been shown to be a member of the LsyE superfamily. Therefore, these proteins are most likely secondary carriers.
The proposed generalized reaction catalyzed by members of the GAP family is:
PGL (in) → PGL (outer membrane).{{r|tcdb}}
