In [[maximum parsimony]], an '''informative site''' is a position in the relevant set of sequences at which there are at least two different [[character state]]s at that point in the sequences, and each of those states occurs in at least two of the sequences. Character states can take on multiple types of data, including [[Morphology_(biology)|morphological]] (such as the presence of wings, tentacles, etc.) or [[Molecular phylogenetics|molecular information]] such as sequences of [[DNA]] or [[proteins]].
[[File:Parsimony informative v1.svg|thumb|Example of parsimony informative sites. In phylogenetics, parsimony informative sites are those with at least two states. Here, this is sites 2 and 4. Site 2 indicates a grouping of Species A and C, while site 4 indicates a grouping of Species A and B. Because these two sites conflict, other analyses (such as [[maximum likelihood]]) are needed to resolve the phylogenetic tree of these four species.]]

