A '''biconcave disc''' — also referred to as a discocyte<ref name="kuchelfackerell">{{Cite journal |last=Kuchel |first=Philip W. |last2=Fackerell |first2=Edward D. |year=1999 |title=Parametric-equation representation of biconcave erythrocytes |journal=Bulletin of Mathematical Biology |language=en |volume=61 |issue=2 |pages=209–220 |doi=10.1006/bulm.1998.0064 |issn=1522-9602 }}</ref> — is a geometric shape resembling an [[oblate spheroid]] with two [[Concavity|concavities]] on the top and on the bottom. It is [[meta-stable]], and involves the continuous adjustment of the asymmetric transbilayer lipid distribution, which is correlated with [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]] depletion.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Pages |first=Guilhem |last2=Yau |first2=Tsz W. |last3=Kuchel |first3=Philip W. |date=2010 |title=Erythrocyte shape reversion from echinocytes to discocytes: Kinetics via fast-measurement NMR diffusion-diffraction |journal=Magnetic Resonance in Medicine |language=en |volume=64 |issue=3 |pages=645–652 |doi=10.1002/mrm.22457 |pmid=20806372 }}</ref>

