{{About|chemical structures that look biological but are not||Fossils|and|Gardening|and|Victor A. Tiedjens}}
{{merge to|Chemical garden|date=November 2019}}
{{use dmy dates |date=November 2019}}
{{short description|forming chemicals that look biological but are not}}
'''Chemical gardening''' refers to the process of creating complex biological-looking structures by mixing chemicals together wherever large amounts of such chemicals naturally occur. More simply, forming natural minerals to mimic biology. For example, mixing iron-rich particles with alkaline liquids containing the chemicals silicate or carbonate have created biological-looking structures. Such structures are actually non-biological even though they may appear to be biological and/or [[fossil]]s.<ref name="EA-20191127" /><ref name="TRS-20191127" /><ref name="PT-20160301">{{cite journal |author=Steinbock, Oliver |display-authors=et al. |title=The fertile physics of chemical gardens |url=https://physicstoday.scitation.org/doi/full/10.1063/PT.3.3108 |date=1 March 2019 |journal=[[physics Today]] |volume=69 |issue=3 |page=44 |doi=10.1063/PT.3.3108 |accessdate=27 November 2019 }}</ref> According to researchers, "Chemical reactions like these have been studied for hundreds of years but they had not previously been shown to mimic these tiny iron-rich structures inside rocks. These results call for a re-examination of many ancient real-world examples to see if they are more likely to be fossils or non-biological mineral deposits."<ref name="EA-20191127" /><ref name="TRS-20191127" />

One use of the study of chemical gardening is to be better able to distinguish biological structures, including [[fossil]]s, from non-biological structures on the planet [[Mars]].<ref name="EA-20191127">{{cite news |author=[[University of Edinburgh]] |title=Solving fossil mystery could aid quest for ancient life on Mars |url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2019-11/uoe-sfm112719.php |date=27 November 2019 |work=[[EurekAlert!]] |accessdate=27 November 2019 }}</ref><ref name="TRS-20191127">{{cite journal |last=McMahon |first=Sean |title=Earth's earliest and deepest purported fossils may be iron-mineralized chemical gardens |url=https://royalsocietypublishing.org/doi/10.1098/rspb.2019.2410 |date=27 November 2019 |journal=[[Proceedings of the Royal Society B]] |doi=10.1098/rspb.2019.2410 |accessdate=27November 2019 }}</ref>

