{{Short description|Deliberate action to guide decisions to achieve beneficial outcome}} {{Multiple issues|{{cleanup|date=January 2019|reason=use of bolded terms}}{{original research|date=January 2019}}}}
'''Delaying tactic''' is a deliberate action to guide decisions to achieve beneficial outcomes, by delaying a decision, or an occurrence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/delaying+tactic|title=Definition of DELAYING TACTIC|website=Merriam-webster.com|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> or by slowing it down to win an advantage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/delaying-tactics|title=DELAYING TACTICS - meaning in the Cambridge English Dictionary|website=Dictionary.cambridge.org|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref> Many governments, and organizations are accused of applying such tactics,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/video/2017/08/06/china-cooperation-asean-over-disputed-territory-could-be-a-delaying-tactic.html|title=China's cooperation with ASEAN could be a delaying tactic|website=Cnbc.com|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/egypts-delaying-tactic/2011/10/10/gIQAMlkYaL_story.html?noredirect=on |title=Archived copy |access-date=2019-01-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190111054912/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/egypts-delaying-tactic/2011/10/10/gIQAMlkYaL_story.html?noredirect=on&utm_term=.2f106d76bf7e |archive-date=2019-01-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/roomfordebate/2013/09/11/can-syrias-chemical-arsenal-be-destroyed/a-delaying-tactic-to-stall-assads-fall|title=A Delaying Tactic to Stall Assad's Fall|website=Nytimes.com|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/oil-spill-research-1.4526967|title=Call for more oil spill research not a delaying tactic, says B.C. NDP - CBC News|author=Matt Humphrey|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bangladesh-politics-exclusive/exclusive-myanmars-delaying-tactics-blocking-rohingya-return-bangladesh-pm-idUSKCN1M60N] {{dead link|date=January 2019}}</ref> some examples of delaying tactics are:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://simplicable.com/new/negotiation-tactics|title=28 Examples of Negotiation Tactics|website=Simplicable.com|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://playbook.amanet.org/the-5-most-common-negotiation-tactics-and-how-to-counter-them-ama-research/|title=The 5 Most Common Negotiation Tactics and How to Counter Them: AMA Research -|date=6 April 2015|website=Playbook.amanet.org|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pon.harvard.edu/daily/batna/10-hardball-tactics-in-negotiation/|title=10 Hard-Bargaining Tactics & Negotiation Skills|date=7 January 2019|publisher=|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://changingminds.org/disciplines/negotiation/tactics/tactics.htm|title=Negotiation Tactics|website=Changingminds.org|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>
* '''Active silence:''' The negotiator uses silence skillfully to induce a targeted discomfort in the other parties. * '''Bigger picture:''' The negotiator makes light of the proposed issue, and turns the focus to a wider discussion. * '''[[Bluff (poker)|Bluff]]:''' The negotiator makes a false claim, as if he has better offers from other parties. * '''[[Bogeyman]]:''' The negotiator introduces a false threat or warning. * '''Changing the Negotiator:''' The negotiator is changed to reset the progression made thus far. * '''[[Political agenda|Control the Agenda]]:''' The negotiator controls the [[Political agenda|agenda]], and the priorities to control what is discussed and when. * '''[[Divide and rule|Divide and conquer]]:''' The negotiator creates an internal conflict between other parties who are opposed to them. * '''[[Ellsberg paradox]]''' or also [[ambiguity aversion]]''':''' The negotiator uses the human bias toward choosing the option that they know more about, despite of its real merits. * '''Empty Promises:''' The negotiator makes promises that they know they will not keep. * '''[[Insult|Feather ruffling]]:''' The negotiator utilizes [[Ad hominem|personal attack]] to divert the discussion to the involved parties instead of the results. * '''Fragmentation:''' The negotiator breaks the discussion into minor discussions. * '''Introducing a new issue:''' The negotiator introduces a new issue during the negotiation for distraction. * '''Late objections:''' The negotiator makes an objection late in the negotiation, to set it back to [[Square-1 (puzzle)|square one]]. * '''Limited Authority,''' or '''Missing person tactic:''' The [[Negotiation|negotiator]] declares their limited ability to make a decision. * '''[[Logrolling]]:''' The negotiator concedes on low-priority items to them. * '''Overwhelming:''' The negotiator provides other parties with too much requests or information to overload them. * '''Questioning goals:''' The negotiator debates the value of other parties' ultimate goals. * '''Phasing:''' The negotiator offers to phase in or out the requested changes, buying themselves more time. * '''Playing Dumb:''' The negotiator acts stupid to avoid confrontations. * '''Selective listening:''' The negotiator overlooks certain fragments of the other parties' argument.
